<DOC><DOCNO> AP901218-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-18-90 1531EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-BusAccident 2ndLd-Writethru a0615 12-18 0238</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bus Accident, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0615,0270</SECOND><HEAD>Bus, Tractor-Trailer Rig Collide On Freeway; Six Reported Dead</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 7 dead, 16 injured. Picksup6th graf pvs., `Two medical ...'</NOTE><DATELINE>EMORY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Greyhound bus collided with twotractor-trailer rigs near the Wyoming state line today. Sevenpeople were killed and 16 were injured, authorities said.   Summit County Sheriff's Sgt. Robert Berry said five of theinjured were in ``very critical'' condition following the 9 a.m.crash.   Blaine Whimpe, a witness, said a westbound truck apparently slidoff Interstate 80 into the eastbound lanes, colliding with a secondtruck and the bus.   It appeared the bus turned on its side and slid about 150 feet,he said, adding that the road condition was ``terrible.'' TheNational Weather Service said there was snow and wind gusting to 29mph at Evanston, Wyo., at the time of the crash.   The injured were being treated at Evanston Regional Hospitalabout 10 miles from the accident site, three or four with headinjuries, said Craig Rasmussen of LDS Hospital, a sister facilityin Salt Lake City.   Two medical helicopters and a plane were sent from LDS Hospital,he said.   Greyhound dispatcher Bill Moore said the bus left Salt Lake Cityat 8 a.m. en route to Chicago with more than 40 passengers aboard.Greyhound inspectors were dispatched to the accident.   The Wyoming Army National Guard armory in Evanston has beenopened for travelers who were on the bus, according to Sgt. BobJune, unit administrator for Battery C, Third Battalion, 49th FieldArtillery.</TEXT></DOC>